them: And here he &s;aid a great many hand&s;ome
Things indeed of the little Concern Men gene|rally
took upon them&s;elves either to marry religi|ous
Wives, or to &s;ee that the Opinions of tho&s;e
they mar$ied were not too much &s;hocking with
their own; and e&s;pecially that when Men had re|ligious
Wives, or Women had religious Husbands,
they did not &s;tudy, as much as lay in them, on both
&s;ides, to bring their Opinions to agaee with one
